  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I trace my family line to make sure I'm not in love with my cousin?",
  "response": "Tracing your family lineage to ensure you're not closely related to someone you're romantically interested in can be a meticulous process. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you trace your family line:\n\n1. **Gather Family Information:**\n   - Start by collecting information from your immediate family members. Gather names, birthdates, birthplaces, marriage details, and any other relevant data.\n   - Use family records like birth certificates, marriage licenses, and old family letters.\n\n2. **Interview Relatives:**\n   - Talk to older relatives who might have more knowledge about your family history. They can provide anecdotes and details not found in documents.\n   - Ask for stories or details about extended family members.\n\n3. **Create a Family Tree:**\n   - Use the information gathered to create a family tree. Begin with yourself and work your way backward, adding all relatives and any known links.\n   - There are many online tools and software, such as Ancestry.com, FamilySearch.org, or MyHeritage, which can help organize and visualize this data.\n\n4. **Examine Public Records:**\n   - Access public records through online databases or local archives for additional documentation like census records, immigration records, wills, and obituaries.\n   - Libraries and government offices often have genealogical sections.\n\n5. **Explore Genealogical Websites:**\n   - Use websites tailored for genealogy research. Many of these databases allow you to search records and potentially connect with other distant relatives who might have additional information.\n   - DNA testing services like 23andMe or AncestryDNA can provide insight into your genetic background and identify potential relatives.\n\n6. **Map Connections:**\n   - Once you have a comprehensive family tree, examine the connections between your family and the family of the person you\u2019re interested in. Identify any potential overlaps or common ancestors.\n   \n7. **Utilize DNA Testing:**\n   - Consider using DNA testing to find potential familial ties. These tests can reveal shared DNA and indicate how closely related you might be to someone.\n   - Carefully read results and reports, focusing on the degree of relation suggested by the genetic data.\n\n8. **Consult a Professional Genealogist:**\n   - If the task becomes overwhelming, you might consider hiring a professional genealogist. They have expertise in tracing family lines and can access resources you might not easily find.\n\nTaking these steps should give you a clearer picture of your family history and help ensure that you are not in a close kinship relationship with your romantic interest. Remember, for most issues related to distant cousins, the likelihood of significant genetic overlap is minimal, but it is always worth being informed.",
